              <p>Linux is an open-source operating system kernel used across servers, desktops, embedded devices, and more. Popular distributions include Ubuntu, Fedora, and Arch.</p>
            </section>

            <section>
              <h2>Why use Linux?</h2>
              <p>Linux offers performance, security, and flexibility. It’s excellent for development, learning systems, and server administration.</p>
              <h3>Key benefits</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>Open-source and community-driven</li>
                <li>Powerful command line tooling</li>
                <li>Stable and secure</li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <section>
              <h2>Installing a distribution</h2>
              <p>You can install Linux alongside Windows (dual-boot) or run it in a virtual machine. Start with Ubuntu LTS for stability.</p>
            </section>

            <section>
              <h2>First steps in the terminal</h2>
              <p>Learn basic commands like cd, ls, cp, mv, rm, mkdir, and man. Package managers (apt, dnf, pacman) help you install software.</p>
            </section>

            <section>
              <h2>Next steps</h2>
              <p>Explore shell scripting, systemd services, and SSH. Consider learning Git for version control and Docker for containers.</p>
